<font color="#0080ff">www.</font>addic7ed<font color="#0080ff">.com</font>

00:29.521 --> 00:31.313
ANNOUNCER:
<i>Bottom of the ninth, two outs.</i>

00:31.410 --> 00:33.182
<i>Could the Reds pull off the impossible</i>

00:33.207 --> 00:36.495
<i>and upset the heavily favored White
Sox to win the World Series?</i>

00:36.520 --> 00:37.870
It's so clear.

00:37.895 --> 00:39.613
It's like we're actually there.

00:39.649 --> 00:40.950
- Totally.
- Technology is amazing.

00:40.975 --> 00:43.253
<i>Up to bat comes Shoeless Joe Jackson.</i>

00:43.278 --> 00:46.253
Yeah, it's kind of crazy...
if this World Series bet

00:46.289 --> 00:48.422
goes through, you're
gonna make a lot of money,

00:48.496 --> 00:49.790
and if it don't,

00:49.957 --> 00:51.525
I'm gonna kill you.

00:51.561 --> 00:52.426
So crazy.

00:52.462 --> 00:54.595
(Chris laughs nervously)

00:54.630 --> 00:56.784
<i>Here's the pitch. Shoeless Joe swings.</i>

00:56.809 --> 00:59.621
<i>It's a ground ball up the middle
of the field. Rath fields it.</i>

00:59.646 --> 01:03.315
<i>Throws to first... and he's out...
that's the ball game!</i>

01:03.340 --> 01:05.483
- <i>The Reds win the World Series!</i>
- (cheering)

01:05.509 --> 01:07.708
CAPONE: We did it, Danny! We're rich!

01:07.733 --> 01:11.688
DEBORAH: I'm just glad it's over.
Baseball is so dull!

01:11.821 --> 01:15.665
Hey, could someone take a picture
of the winners over here?

01:16.419 --> 01:17.485
(flashbulb pops)

01:17.520 --> 01:18.853
- (screams)
- Wow!

01:18.888 --> 01:20.454
(gasping, screaming)

01:20.490 --> 01:22.356
Oh, my God!

01:22.391 --> 01:24.525
♪ ♪

01:24.860 --> 01:27.594
I've only ever done
this with fresh milk.

01:27.652 --> 01:31.355
Hey, you better not spill any,
or I'll strangle Dan! (chuckles)

01:32.511 --> 01:34.761
To our wonderful new friends,

01:35.004 --> 01:37.501
Daniel, Deborah and Johnny No-Fun.

01:37.526 --> 01:40.675
- It's Chris.
- Fine. Chris No-Fun.

01:40.810 --> 01:43.677
May this be the beginning
of a long relationship.

01:43.712 --> 01:44.778
<i>Salud!</i>

01:44.814 --> 01:45.913
OTHERS: <i>Salud!</i>

01:47.408 --> 01:49.401
DAN: Hey, Deb, check it out.

01:49.426 --> 01:52.018
- I'm Mr. Bread-Hands.
- (squealing laugh)

01:52.489 --> 01:55.635
DEBORAH: That is the funniest
use of bread I've ever seen.

01:55.660 --> 01:57.885
- Wait, say it into the mic.
- (squeals)

01:58.370 --> 02:00.845
I hate to mix business
with pleasure, Mr. Capone,

02:00.877 --> 02:04.041
but we kind of need our money
and the bag.

02:04.366 --> 02:07.089
(sighs) This guy and his bag.

02:07.203 --> 02:09.823
"The bag, the bag!" (groans)

02:09.848 --> 02:11.823
I told this guy,
if he loves that bag so much,

02:11.848 --> 02:13.698
- why doesn't he just marry it?
- Hmm.

02:13.909 --> 02:16.407
- How do you think <i> that</i> might go?
- I don't know.

02:16.813 --> 02:20.579
Well, there'd be a ceremony,
and it'd be like, "Do you, Chris,

02:20.733 --> 02:24.382
"take this bag to be your
lawfully wedded bag wife,

02:24.407 --> 02:26.471
- (laughing)
- "to have and to hold things...

02:26.535 --> 02:28.755
- 'cause you're a bag..."
- (laughing)

02:28.791 --> 02:30.057
Chris would say "I do."

02:30.092 --> 02:32.566
- (others laughing)
- And then, uh... they'd say,

02:32.590 --> 02:34.356
"Bag, do you...

02:34.410 --> 02:36.963
" Love it, Danny! I can't breathe!

02:36.988 --> 02:40.000
That's the funniest
thing I've ever heard!

02:40.035 --> 02:41.935
(laughter continues)

02:41.971 --> 02:43.667
Deborah, can you please pass the bread?

02:43.692 --> 02:46.373
No. No more bread for her.
She's getting fat.

02:46.408 --> 02:47.708
Al...

02:47.753 --> 02:49.826
I had the baby a week ago.

02:49.959 --> 02:52.605
Yeah? Then why do you still
look like the <i> Lusitania?</i>

02:52.630 --> 02:54.319
I mean, she's a big boat, right?

02:54.354 --> 02:56.821
I mean, I'm getting seasick
just looking at her!

02:56.846 --> 02:57.920
(laughter)

02:57.945 --> 03:01.311
- (imitating ship's horn blowing)
- N-No... No.

03:01.495 --> 03:03.394
(crying): Thanks a lot, Al.

03:05.832 --> 03:07.432
Excuse me.

03:09.367 --> 03:11.100
(sighs)

03:11.125 --> 03:12.525
Congrats on the baby.

03:12.550 --> 03:14.172
- Shut up.
- Yes, sir.

03:17.110 --> 03:18.501
Mae?

03:18.884 --> 03:21.204
You don't have to take that.

03:21.486 --> 03:24.423
(sighs) That's men for you.
They're all the same.

03:24.448 --> 03:25.548
Daniel isn't.

03:25.572 --> 03:28.547
Yeah, but you got a guy who's doing
a whole bread routine for you,

03:28.572 --> 03:30.242
and I'm married to Al Capone.

03:30.267 --> 03:31.589
I mean, what am I gonna do?

03:32.626 --> 03:33.658
Mae...

03:33.981 --> 03:35.763
I don't know you very well,

03:36.067 --> 03:37.729
but I like you,

03:38.356 --> 03:40.284
and I want to tell you a secret.

03:40.402 --> 03:42.126
- You're Jewish?
- No.

03:42.193 --> 03:43.841
Oh. Phew!

03:43.866 --> 03:47.936
Times are changing for us.
We're going to be able to vote soon.

03:48.006 --> 03:52.502
And I even heard that in Baltimore,
a man made his own dinner.

03:52.748 --> 03:54.704
- What?
- Mae,

03:55.015 --> 03:56.739
your life can be better.

03:56.775 --> 03:59.904
Oh, my God. We-we have
to get back to the table.

03:59.929 --> 04:02.178
Al is gonna think I'm moving my bowels.

04:03.882 --> 04:05.882
♪ ♪

04:08.911 --> 04:10.344
Mmm!

04:10.710 --> 04:12.328
What a steak!

04:12.353 --> 04:14.265
- How's yours, guys?
- Great, boss.

04:14.290 --> 04:16.134
- Terrific.
- Fantastic.

04:16.158 --> 04:19.252
CHRIS: It's a little rare for my
taste but it's still good.

04:22.100 --> 04:25.145
Excuse me for a moment,
would you, please?

04:28.496 --> 04:31.007
- (gunshot)
- (thump in distance)

04:31.870 --> 04:33.870
(footsteps approaching)

04:35.135 --> 04:37.049
They're gonna bring you a new one.

04:37.678 --> 04:39.103
DEBORAH: What did we miss?

04:39.205 --> 04:40.850
DAN: Guy stuff, bro-ing out.

04:40.885 --> 04:42.385
I need to digest a little.

04:42.420 --> 04:44.247
- Let's take a stroll.
- Yeah, I could do a walk.

04:44.272 --> 04:45.855
All right. Not you!

04:45.890 --> 04:48.334
You stay here with the
women and the nobodies.

04:48.960 --> 04:50.616
Let's go, Danny.

04:51.508 --> 04:53.529
I've never seen a
little guy eat so much.

04:53.557 --> 04:56.451
Aw, Al. Little. Thank you so much.

04:56.484 --> 04:57.867
Mm. You know, Dan...

04:58.336 --> 05:01.214
I like you, and I don't...
I don't got a lot of friends.

05:01.239 --> 05:03.755
Oh, stop. What about that
big guy who can't stop burping?

05:03.780 --> 05:06.356
- He seems like a cool cat.
- He's not like <i> you.</i>

05:06.411 --> 05:09.312
I mean, you're smart,
fun, funny, nice, cool.

05:09.645 --> 05:12.634
You know? And I feel
like after I pay you,

05:12.667 --> 05:14.450
I'm never gonna see you again.

05:14.977 --> 05:16.537
I'll give you my e-mail.

05:16.700 --> 05:18.872
- What?
- What? What did you hear,

05:18.897 --> 05:21.028
and then I can, um,
tell you what I said.

05:21.061 --> 05:22.892
No, I just, I just feel
like you're gonna,

05:22.927 --> 05:24.590
you know, blow town, you know?

05:24.615 --> 05:26.262
You got your crew.

05:26.703 --> 05:30.303
- That Chris character.
- Oh, yeah, yeah, he can be a pill.

05:30.328 --> 05:31.501
He's so negative!

05:31.536 --> 05:33.255
It's, like, I could tell,
when I killed that waiter,

05:33.280 --> 05:34.584
he was, like, judging me.

05:34.608 --> 05:36.639
It's so hard to build up confidence,

05:36.674 --> 05:38.859
and then a guy like that can
just snatch it away from you

05:38.884 --> 05:41.172
- with just a look.
- Yeah, exactly.

05:41.593 --> 05:42.828
Anyway...

05:42.922 --> 05:44.414
here's your cut of the dough.

05:44.658 --> 05:46.626
I-I love dough.

05:47.014 --> 05:49.491
I love dough so much
I might marry a pizza.

05:49.562 --> 05:52.475
(laughs) Imagine if you married a pizza,

05:52.500 --> 05:54.123
how <i> that</i> might go!

05:54.159 --> 05:56.025
(laughing)

05:56.060 --> 05:58.258
Oh, man!

05:58.396 --> 06:00.163
(laughing)

06:00.526 --> 06:02.440
Uh, hey, Al.

06:02.799 --> 06:05.666
Do you think maybe I could get
my money in, uh,<i> my</i> bag?

06:05.744 --> 06:06.969
The one that's in your vault.

06:07.284 --> 06:09.272
Oh, yeah. That's it. That's the bag.

06:09.297 --> 06:11.390
This isn't my bag.
My bag was-was bigger.

06:11.415 --> 06:13.776
No, I remember. Tiny little bag.

06:13.812 --> 06:17.976
Al, my bag was so big, you could fit
two to three bodies in it.

06:18.001 --> 06:19.885
You could fit two to three
bodies in there, Danny.

06:19.910 --> 06:22.580
- Now, I hate to argue with you, Al...
- You know what?

06:22.697 --> 06:24.400
Then don't.

06:25.310 --> 06:29.013
I think you and me are gonna be spending
a lot more time together than you think.

06:29.334 --> 06:32.395
I'd like that <i> very</i> much.

06:32.617 --> 06:36.234
Now, walk me through this pizza wedding!

06:36.295 --> 06:37.586
(laughs)

06:38.058 --> 06:40.091
(excited shouts, laughing)

06:41.870 --> 06:44.124
Hey. What are you doing?

06:44.219 --> 06:46.108
We were supposed to be
in the lobby two hours ago.

06:46.195 --> 06:48.302
Gee, I'm sorry, Chris,
that we weren't up

06:48.327 --> 06:50.785
to make it to your big
stuck-in-the-past breakfast.

06:50.810 --> 06:52.606
DAN: We were up late doing sarcasm.

06:52.631 --> 06:54.107
Oh, were we?

06:54.132 --> 06:55.935
- (laughs): So funny.
- Well, I hate to interrupt

06:55.960 --> 06:58.495
your romantic trip, but we need
to take down Al Capone

06:58.520 --> 07:00.126
so we can get our time machine back.

07:00.204 --> 07:03.125
Oh, Chris... we already took care of it.

07:04.118 --> 07:05.368
How?

07:05.627 --> 07:08.079
Uh, we're gonna
"Donnie Brasco" Capone...

07:08.227 --> 07:10.329
earn his trust and then make him
take us to his vault.

07:10.399 --> 07:13.282
- That doesn't sound safe for Deb.
- Oh. Sexist.

07:13.307 --> 07:15.847
What are you gonna say to that?
There's no comeback.

07:15.972 --> 07:17.081
Okay, while you two

07:17.106 --> 07:19.206
are busy playing Mafia,
I also came up with a plan.

07:19.417 --> 07:22.651
And it has the benefit of being
the actual thing that takes down Capone.

07:22.778 --> 07:24.752
- What is it?
- I am gonna go

07:24.777 --> 07:27.317
to the Internal Revenue Service
and report on Capone's

07:27.349 --> 07:29.753
very specious accounting practices.

07:29.778 --> 07:30.817
DAN: You're gonna tell on him.

07:30.842 --> 07:32.508
- Very cool.
- Sarcasm.

07:32.538 --> 07:33.850
- Yeah.
- Mm.

07:33.875 --> 07:35.788
Okay, this isn't a movie. It's history.

07:35.824 --> 07:37.892
- Movies are fiction.
- What about <i> Hoop Dreams?</i>

07:37.917 --> 07:39.259
- That was a documentary.
- What's the difference?

07:39.337 --> 07:41.173
I believe a documentary's
based on actual events,

07:41.243 --> 07:43.259
whereas a movie is
just completely made up.

07:43.384 --> 07:44.666
See? Even she gets it.

07:44.702 --> 07:46.009
(takes deep breath)

07:46.033 --> 07:47.046
That's sexist.

07:47.071 --> 07:49.626
I was saying that because you're
a Colonial, not because you're a woman.

07:49.774 --> 07:52.001
You're digging your own grave, you pig.

07:53.277 --> 07:55.110
Fat Tony. Fat Jimmy.

07:55.226 --> 07:56.851
Tony. Jimmy.

07:56.891 --> 07:59.872
- Hey, uh, Al.
- Hey... buddies!

07:59.897 --> 08:01.856
While we were waiting,
we-we had a thought.

08:01.881 --> 08:04.153
- Uh, what if we didn't go
- We... Yeah.

08:04.178 --> 08:06.529
to a restaurant for lunch,
but we had, like, a picnic?

08:06.554 --> 08:08.812
Yes, in your vault.

08:09.132 --> 08:10.592
What if we did it in your vault?

08:10.628 --> 08:11.929
Yeah. That would be funny.

08:11.954 --> 08:13.539
It would be so funny, 'cause people

08:13.564 --> 08:15.435
- don't usually eat in vaults, and, well,
- Yeah.

08:15.470 --> 08:17.309
we would all be sitting there
eating in the vault,

08:17.334 --> 08:19.168
- near the... near the bag.
- Yeah. Yeah.

08:19.203 --> 08:21.849
Nah. I guess that's just
not my type of humor. Okay?

08:21.874 --> 08:24.614
I want to go to a restaurant.
Now, can I finish up work real fast?

08:24.639 --> 08:27.209
Give me my money, scumbag!

08:27.244 --> 08:28.830
- But I...
- Aah!

08:30.071 --> 08:31.337
(gasps)

08:33.517 --> 08:34.683
What restaurant were you thinking?

08:34.717 --> 08:37.407
Fact: Al Capone
was actually brought down

08:37.432 --> 08:39.307
by the Internal Revenue Service,

08:39.423 --> 08:43.025
which is why I'm here... at
the Internal Revenue Service.

08:46.669 --> 08:47.935
That's rude.

08:48.271 --> 08:49.331
E-Excuse me?

08:49.693 --> 08:53.232
What number's next? I have, uh... 26.

08:54.161 --> 08:55.251
Four.

08:55.372 --> 08:57.539
Won't be long now.

08:57.969 --> 09:01.132
DAN: Al, you wanted to be smart,
fun, funny and nice like me?

09:01.157 --> 09:02.907
This is not the way I would handle it.

09:03.180 --> 09:07.016
Okay. So if a guy can't pay me,
what do you suppose I do, exactly?

09:07.117 --> 09:09.688
Well, maybe you be nicer
and not kill him?

09:10.149 --> 09:12.008
(sighs): That's crazy,

09:12.133 --> 09:13.388
but I'll give it a shot.

09:13.424 --> 09:14.890
Speak of the devil.

09:15.000 --> 09:17.225
Here he is. Huh, Al?

09:17.250 --> 09:19.495
Don't you have something to
say to this nice florist?

09:20.281 --> 09:22.919
Sorry that I bashed your face in.

09:23.234 --> 09:24.763
Is it bad?

09:24.935 --> 09:26.602
What do you want to hear, man?

09:26.637 --> 09:28.170
(whimpers)

09:28.622 --> 09:30.544
Dan, I am so confused.

09:30.637 --> 09:32.604
This guy owes me money,
and he's still alive.

09:32.628 --> 09:36.278
What if, instead of him giving you
the five dollars that he owes you...

09:36.972 --> 09:39.448
he gives you $20 worth
of flowers from his shop?

09:39.557 --> 09:41.589
What am I gonna do
with a bunch of flowers?

09:41.613 --> 09:44.198
Well, maybe you can give
them to your wife Mae.

09:44.223 --> 09:47.128
If Mae wants flowers, she can go
to the churchyard and pick 'em.

09:47.253 --> 09:50.658
A little romantic gesture
goes a long way.

09:50.761 --> 09:52.528
Dan gave me a snow globe.

09:52.775 --> 09:56.055
It was very heavy and started
leaking almost immediately,

09:56.080 --> 09:57.463
but, oh, I loved it.

09:57.488 --> 09:59.101
Oh, my God, fine!

09:59.136 --> 10:01.036
Give me the dumb flowers
for my stupid wife.

10:01.534 --> 10:03.572
He's gonna take the flowers
for his dumb wife.

10:04.377 --> 10:06.342
DAN: See, Al? You keep it
up with this nice stuff,

10:06.367 --> 10:08.428
and all over town people'll
be doing favors for you.

10:08.453 --> 10:10.828
You'll be known as... a Godfather.

10:10.984 --> 10:12.945
FLORIST: That's actually
a good description,

10:13.039 --> 10:14.532
because I'm not related to him, but he has

10:14.557 --> 10:16.518
a sort of paternal interest
in my well-being.

10:20.257 --> 10:22.057
(sighs)

10:22.340 --> 10:24.236
I just found him irritating.

10:24.568 --> 10:26.329
But you didn't kill him.

10:27.540 --> 10:29.641
I didn't kill him.

10:34.625 --> 10:35.843
Hey, Mae.

10:36.406 --> 10:38.718
Hay is for horses. What do you want?

10:38.976 --> 10:41.243
♪ ♪

10:42.038 --> 10:43.656
That... dish towel

10:43.796 --> 10:45.882
really brings out your eyes.

10:48.390 --> 10:49.985
Very funny, Al.

10:50.351 --> 10:52.715
Eat your pot roast before it gets cold.

11:01.966 --> 11:02.931
(sighs)

11:03.172 --> 11:04.712
(banging)

11:04.766 --> 11:08.203
(groans) To think our ride home is just
on the other side of this door.

11:08.493 --> 11:10.472
Have you tried the handle?

11:11.837 --> 11:14.543
Well, that would be real egg
on my face, huh?

11:17.104 --> 11:19.401
Good. It's locked.

11:19.984 --> 11:22.851
Maybe the door is connected to
these books, like in <i> Scooby-Doo.</i>

11:27.091 --> 11:29.725
(books thumping on floor)

11:30.072 --> 11:32.187
Just try 'em all.

11:37.177 --> 11:39.845
(both laughing)

11:40.201 --> 11:42.638
The lovebirds sound like
they're having a good time.

11:42.732 --> 11:44.506
Must be nice.

11:46.647 --> 11:49.578
Mae, your skin is so soft,
and you can read a clock really fast.

11:49.613 --> 11:51.552
I bought you these flowers,
but then I got scared

11:51.577 --> 11:55.083
and I sat on them instead of giving 'em
to you, but now I am giving 'em to you.

11:55.311 --> 11:58.515
Al, you've never brought me
flowers before.

11:58.585 --> 12:02.107
Mae, I haven't treated you very good
because I was afraid you'd wise up

12:02.132 --> 12:03.892
to how great you are and you'd leave me.

12:03.927 --> 12:06.028
Oh, Al, I could never leave you.

12:06.063 --> 12:07.429
I'm too scared.

12:07.943 --> 12:09.731
That is beautiful.

12:10.038 --> 12:12.411
Mae, you are my partner in love,

12:12.456 --> 12:15.114
my partner in life and my partner in...

12:15.396 --> 12:17.993
Well, I guess "life" just kind of
covers everything, doesn't it?

12:18.018 --> 12:19.374
I should've said "life" first.

12:19.410 --> 12:21.610
Oh, Al, I liked that you said "love."

12:21.645 --> 12:23.178
Love is part of life.

12:23.315 --> 12:24.713
It is now.

12:24.756 --> 12:27.957
♪ ♪

12:27.993 --> 12:30.064
I'm sorry this isn't more romantic.

12:30.154 --> 12:33.478
I'm having a wonderful time...
because I'm with you.

12:33.946 --> 12:35.557
(footsteps approaching)

12:35.592 --> 12:37.225
Oh, he's coming.

12:39.774 --> 12:41.976
These chairs are so comfortable to sit in,

12:42.001 --> 12:43.765
which is all <i> we've</i> been doing.

12:43.792 --> 12:45.350
- Yeah, how'd it go, pal?
- She loved it

12:45.384 --> 12:48.816
so much, and she gave me big kissies.

12:49.306 --> 12:51.345
Honestly, I'm looking forward
to taking credit

12:51.370 --> 12:52.573
for more of your ideas.

12:52.597 --> 12:55.658
How would you two
like to be my... right-hand man

12:55.683 --> 12:57.579
and my left-hand...

12:57.818 --> 12:59.281
not a man?

12:59.787 --> 13:02.461
DAN: Like a... consigliere?

13:03.185 --> 13:04.396
Yeah. I don't know.

13:04.490 --> 13:06.054
- Sure.
- These advisors,

13:06.090 --> 13:09.067
I assume, would have full access
to your life and business

13:09.092 --> 13:11.233
and... I don't know, perhaps your vault?

13:11.261 --> 13:13.236
- (whispers): Nice.
- Yes.

13:13.367 --> 13:15.167
You would be involved in everything.

13:15.265 --> 13:18.100
But this kind of trust is
a really big deal for me.

13:18.360 --> 13:21.356
So I need you to do
a little something for me

13:21.389 --> 13:23.105
to prove your loyalty.

13:23.561 --> 13:25.640
Oh, yeah. Anything.

13:26.171 --> 13:27.943
I need you to kill Chris.

13:31.167 --> 13:33.205
- Yeah. I mean, I don't think that
- Absolutely.

13:33.230 --> 13:34.800
- should be a block in the road.
- I would love to.

13:34.825 --> 13:36.918
- I don't think that's a problem.
- I've been wanting to do that.

13:37.399 --> 13:39.311
- See? It's getting romantic, huh?
- Mm-hmm.

13:39.936 --> 13:42.038
Knock, knock!

13:42.144 --> 13:44.116
(both singing jolly melodies)

13:45.753 --> 13:48.003
DEBORAH: Zing-dee-dee!

13:48.159 --> 13:51.260
- We got pocket watches!
- Pocket watches!

13:53.321 --> 13:55.588
- I have <i> actual</i> good news.
- (gasps)

13:55.702 --> 13:58.077
My plan worked!

13:58.203 --> 13:59.523
That's right, I submitted

13:59.540 --> 14:02.341
the initial paperwork to
the IRS, and after that,

14:02.423 --> 14:06.192
it is mere weeks until they
mail me the forms for the audit.

14:06.227 --> 14:07.641
Oh!

14:07.811 --> 14:11.329
Well, our plan worked, too.
And it'll work right now.

14:11.365 --> 14:13.102
DAN: Yeah. Capone loves us.

14:13.127 --> 14:15.434
All we have to do is show him
a simple act of loyalty.

14:15.459 --> 14:17.593
Yeah. It's not even a big deal.

14:18.691 --> 14:20.053
Okay, like what?

14:20.387 --> 14:22.952
All he wants us to do is
kill you in front of him.

14:22.977 --> 14:24.038
(glass shatters)

14:24.063 --> 14:26.016
Oh, my God!

14:26.040 --> 14:27.756
It's just a watch. Don't worry about it.
It's, like, eight bucks.

14:27.781 --> 14:31.717
I'm not talking about the watch!
I'm talking about being murdered!

14:31.728 --> 14:34.880
He's not actually going
to kill you, Chris.

14:34.905 --> 14:36.028
Yeah, you dum-dum.

14:36.053 --> 14:37.927
When he gives me the gun,
instead of shooting you,

14:37.952 --> 14:39.458
I'll shoot him in the leg.

14:39.483 --> 14:41.160
Yes. And then we'll
make him open the vault

14:41.195 --> 14:42.761
and get our time machine back.

14:42.786 --> 14:44.294
(chuckles): Oh...

14:44.319 --> 14:45.974
No way.

14:46.091 --> 14:48.277
Why? 'Cause <i> you</i> didn't think of it?

14:48.302 --> 14:51.170
No. Because your way brings me
to an execution.

14:51.205 --> 14:54.570
And my way, though it may
seem boring to the uneducated mind,

14:54.647 --> 14:56.350
is the thing in history

14:56.445 --> 14:58.241
that actually takes down Capone.

14:58.335 --> 15:02.623
Well, fine, if you want to wait years
for your IRS scheme to work,

15:02.694 --> 15:03.787
go for it.

15:03.850 --> 15:06.248
<i>Or</i> you could trust your buddy...

15:06.373 --> 15:07.850
now.

15:07.928 --> 15:09.192
I'll take the years.

15:09.217 --> 15:10.536
And when we get the time machine,

15:10.561 --> 15:12.378
I'll just beam back
to the moment we left.

15:12.414 --> 15:13.546
DAN: It doesn't work like that.

15:13.581 --> 15:15.180
However long you're in the past,

15:15.213 --> 15:16.954
that's as long as you've
been gone from the present.

15:16.979 --> 15:19.430
CHRIS: What?
You're just now telling me this?

15:19.526 --> 15:20.730
Yes.

15:20.755 --> 15:23.489
Oh, my God. I've missed a week of class!

15:23.525 --> 15:26.694
I'm not gonna get tenure now.
I may not even have a job!

15:27.515 --> 15:30.116
We got to go to Capone's,
and you got to kill me right now.

15:30.141 --> 15:31.733
And you'd better do a good job.

15:31.758 --> 15:33.368
Oh, yeah, I'll kill you good, boss.

15:35.883 --> 15:38.227
So you're going with
"trust your buddy," huh?

15:38.373 --> 15:39.930
- (door closes)
- Nice.

15:40.542 --> 15:42.341
Watch the walls.

15:42.385 --> 15:43.604
(music playing faintly)

15:43.629 --> 15:44.828
Mae!

15:45.479 --> 15:47.914
If it's not too much trouble,

15:48.377 --> 15:51.204
can I get some coffee for our guests?

15:52.376 --> 15:53.993
It's not ready yet.

15:57.525 --> 15:59.035
That's okay.

16:00.363 --> 16:02.551
What's most important...

16:04.027 --> 16:06.527
is your feelings.

16:12.911 --> 16:14.669
Toodle-loo.

16:19.265 --> 16:22.976
Oh, my God! Oh, my God!

16:23.030 --> 16:25.859
Who was <i> that</i> man?
I didn't even recognize him.

16:25.884 --> 16:28.087
That was your husband, Al!

16:28.753 --> 16:29.939
Oh, y...

16:29.972 --> 16:31.589
No, I know. I was making a joke.

16:31.614 --> 16:33.198
Oh, right.

16:33.355 --> 16:35.434
I didn't know, because it wasn't funny.

16:36.564 --> 16:38.364
(loudly): Oh, hey, Danny,

16:38.399 --> 16:41.300
this is that new gun I've
been wanting to show you.

16:41.336 --> 16:43.269
DAN: Oh, Al, the one I wanted

16:43.294 --> 16:46.869
- to see, with the wood inlays.
- Correct.

16:48.109 --> 16:49.705
Sorry, Chris.

16:49.978 --> 16:52.335
- (cocks hammer)
- That's curtains for you.

16:52.508 --> 16:53.980
Oh, no, Dan.

16:54.108 --> 16:57.475
- How could you betray <i> me?</i>
- Any last woids?

16:58.061 --> 16:59.569
Yes.

17:00.319 --> 17:01.431
Checkmate!

17:01.456 --> 17:03.456
- Ha-ha! You dummy!
- Ha!

17:03.491 --> 17:07.474
You think I'd really kill Chris?
He's, like, my best friend.

17:07.628 --> 17:10.020
You're, like, my third best friend.

17:10.428 --> 17:12.309
Sorry, Al.

17:13.425 --> 17:14.723
CHRIS: Do it.

17:14.810 --> 17:16.387
(clicking)

17:18.339 --> 17:20.006
(clicking continues)

17:21.041 --> 17:22.435
Al?

17:22.646 --> 17:23.965
I think your new gun is broken.

17:23.991 --> 17:26.137
- Ha-ha! Checkmate!
- Fart!

17:26.163 --> 17:29.041
You know, the first five times
I tried this loyalty test,

17:29.184 --> 17:30.463
I got shot.

17:31.088 --> 17:32.346
Then I realized, oh,

17:32.432 --> 17:34.339
I don't have to put any bullets in there.

17:34.364 --> 17:36.542
I know if they're loyal
if they pull the trigger.

17:36.636 --> 17:38.680
And I have my answer now.

17:38.859 --> 17:41.765
You, get in the vault...
I'll deal with you later.

17:44.199 --> 17:46.621
Glad I trusted my buddy.

17:49.707 --> 17:51.537
Fuhgettaboutit.

17:52.151 --> 17:53.450
Ah?

17:55.260 --> 17:58.596
- You betrayed me.
- Al, Allie-boy.

18:01.006 --> 18:05.392
(switch clicks, electrical whining)

18:06.690 --> 18:09.102
Now, this is the door
to Al Capone's vault,

18:09.150 --> 18:12.099
which was famously found
completely empty.

18:13.223 --> 18:14.455
Hi.

18:16.256 --> 18:17.639
Bye.

18:18.158 --> 18:20.558
(electrical whining)

18:20.593 --> 18:22.961
(grunts)

18:23.114 --> 18:25.063
I'm interesting!

18:25.200 --> 18:27.802
And the clarinet is awesome!

18:28.001 --> 18:29.834
And history matters!

18:29.869 --> 18:31.436
How did you get out of the vault?

18:32.139 --> 18:33.577
I'm Batman.

18:33.788 --> 18:34.991
I don't know who that is.

18:35.468 --> 18:37.897
Did somebody just yell, "History matters"?

18:37.968 --> 18:39.294
I didn't hear anything.

18:39.319 --> 18:41.812
No, I-I heard something.
I'm gonna go check it out.

18:41.837 --> 18:44.849
- Mae, wait.
- Hey, get your mitts off me.

18:44.884 --> 18:46.922
Oh!

18:47.220 --> 18:49.493
(both grunt)

18:50.190 --> 18:52.657
Look at us, fighting like men.
(chuckles)

18:52.692 --> 18:55.359
(both grunt)

18:55.512 --> 18:57.112
- Better than men.
- Yeah!

18:57.164 --> 18:58.162
(both grunt)

18:58.187 --> 18:59.826
Ah. Oh.

19:00.200 --> 19:02.299
We're making great strides.

19:02.324 --> 19:04.135
(both yell)

19:04.873 --> 19:07.705
- Lights out.
- DEBORAH: Oh.

19:09.409 --> 19:12.245
- (gun cocks)
- Drop it. No one hurts my baby.

19:12.753 --> 19:14.673
CAPONE: Mae, what are you doing?

19:14.698 --> 19:17.978
Al, last week I wished you were dead.

19:18.003 --> 19:19.102
But this week,

19:19.188 --> 19:20.970
we're not just partners in life,

19:21.087 --> 19:22.938
we're partners in crime.

19:23.118 --> 19:26.460
Yeah, life includes crime.
Don't point the gun at me.

19:26.485 --> 19:28.292
- Point it at them.
- Oh, yeah.

19:28.601 --> 19:29.982
DEBORAH: Excuse me!

19:30.007 --> 19:34.234
No one messes with my
partner in life, meaning Dan.

19:34.390 --> 19:36.367
Hi, Dan. I'm sorry, Chris.

19:36.403 --> 19:38.469
- Drop it.
- No, you drop it.

19:38.505 --> 19:40.505
- No, you drop it.
- You drop it.

19:40.530 --> 19:41.607
- Drop it.
- Drop it.

19:41.632 --> 19:44.051
- Please drop it. Please?
- Come on, Deb, drop it.

19:44.076 --> 19:46.267
- Please drop it.
- Your broad ain't gonna shoot.

19:46.292 --> 19:47.651
She don't got the guts.

19:48.253 --> 19:50.548
Do the thing. Do the thing I taught you.

19:51.676 --> 19:55.019
(as Tony Montana):
Say hello to my little friend!

19:55.044 --> 19:58.579
- (laughs)
- ♪ We're not gonna ever take it ♪

19:58.604 --> 20:01.759
♪ I'm never gonna let you keep me down ♪

20:01.795 --> 20:04.524
♪ I can't feel my heart, it's breaking ♪

20:04.549 --> 20:07.891
♪ I'm never gonna make it another round ♪

20:10.726 --> 20:11.816
Oh.

20:13.294 --> 20:15.147
This is why we time-travel.

20:15.442 --> 20:17.311
Moments like this.

20:17.477 --> 20:21.012
- So awesome.
- Okay, you guys got us.

20:21.615 --> 20:23.017
Open the vault.

20:23.083 --> 20:25.550
♪ ♪

20:28.626 --> 20:31.722
CAPONE: You know, if someone
was gonna rob me blind,

20:31.880 --> 20:34.888
- I'm glad it was you, Dan.
- Al, I'm telling you,

20:34.977 --> 20:37.160
you remember all that <i> Godfather</i>
stuff that we talked about,

20:37.185 --> 20:38.545
and the Mafia will be huge.

20:38.570 --> 20:40.359
You won't even need the money
I took from you.

20:40.384 --> 20:42.826
You taught Al Capone
how to do the Mafia?

20:42.851 --> 20:45.369
Bye-bye, Mae. Bye. Bye.

20:45.850 --> 20:48.194
Al, later, skater.

20:50.944 --> 20:53.044
(electrical whining)

20:53.079 --> 20:55.608
(grunts) Yes, yes, yes.

20:55.633 --> 20:58.883
We are back, and we got the money still.

20:58.908 --> 21:00.946
- (laughter)
- Now we can buy the ice cream parlor.

21:00.971 --> 21:04.655
And most importantly, we saved
Al and Mae Capone's marriage.

21:06.275 --> 21:08.986
- Absolutely, that was number one priority.
- That never mattered at all.

21:10.674 --> 21:14.640
Aw, gross, there's a sandwich in my
pocket that's, like, 100 years old now.

